data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider's **sync-over-async opt-in** (e.g., calling `EnableSyncOverAsync()` on the Cosmos options) let synchronous LINQ operators work by wrapping async calls internally. **In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed entirely.**

Every synchronous call — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime. There is no workaround; the Cosmos provider only supports async operations now.

## The Fix: Convert to Async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
1. Return `Task<T>` / `Task` instead of bare types
2. Mark methods `async`
3. Replace `ToList` → `ToListAsync`, `First` → `FirstAsync`, `Count` → `CountAsync`, `SaveChanges` → `SaveChangesAsync`
4. `await` each call
5. Rename methods with `Async` suffix (convention)
6. Remove the `EnableSyncOverAsync()` call from your `DbContext` configuration — it no longer compiles

You'll also need to propagate `async`/`await` up through every caller in the chain (controllers, services, etc.).
